    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Vocabulary: 'Number' and 'Telephone'"
        },
        "text": "To ask for specific numbers like a phone number, you'll need the words for 'number' and 'telephone'. 'رقم' is formal, while 'نْمرة' is very common and informal.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "رقم",
            "english": "Number (formal)",
            "transliteration": "raqm"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "نْمرة",
            "english": "Number (informal, commonly used)",
            "transliteration": "nemra"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "تليفون",
            "english": "Telephone / Phone",
            "transliteration": "tilifon"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Possessive Pronouns: 'Yours' (ديالك / ديالكِ)"
        },
        "text": "To ask for 'your' number, we use possessive pronouns. 'ديالك' is used for male singular, and 'ديالكِ' for female singular (though often pronounced the same in everyday speech, the written distinction for clarity is good).",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "ديالك",
            "english": "Yours (m.sg)",
            "transliteration": "dialek"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "ديالكِ",
            "english": "Yours (f.sg)",
            "transliteration": "dialek",
            "diacriticalNotes": "Note the kasra on the last letter for feminine, though often pronounced similarly to masculine in speech."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "رقم التليفون ديالك؟",
            "english": "Your phone number?",
            "transliteration": "raqm at-tilifon dialek?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'What is your phone number?'"
        },
        "text": "Combining what we've learned, you can ask for someone's phone number using 'شنو هو...؟' (shnu huwa...? - What is...?) or simply by stating the phrase with a rising intonation.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "شنو هو رقم التليفون ديالك؟",
            "english": "What is your phone number?",
            "transliteration": "shnu huwa raqm at-tilifon dialek?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "نْمرة التليفون ديالك؟",
            "english": "Your phone number?",
            "transliteration": "nemrat at-tilifon dialek?"
          }
        ]
      }
